weapon-type ban
out of Highland Park, Illinois.
The challenge

10:59.792 --> 11:03.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
came there to the Supreme Court
and the Supreme
Court didn't want to take it

11:03.596 --> 11:10.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up. It's not unusual for the
court to allow
certain questions to percolate
in the lower

11:10.169 --> 11:15.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
courts after it's made a major
ruling. And
the major ruling, though, here
came in 2008

11:15.542 --> 11:21.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the so-called Heller decision
involving
the District of Columbia's
handgun ban.

11:21.214 --> 11:25.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they're just -- you need
four votes to
take a case in the Supreme
Court, and they

11:25.585 --> 11:32.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just aren't there, despite some
rather strong
dissents from the denial of a
review by Justices

11:32.659 --> 11:37.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Clarence Thomas, Samuel Alito,
and the late
Antonin Scalia.

11:37.196 --> 11:42.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And those dissents
are about the
right to gun ownership, or what
are they?

11:42.335 --> 11:47.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: They're really
about how the
lower courts have been dealing
with applying

11:47.106 --> 11:50.543 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that 2008 landmark decision.

11:50.577 --> 11:54.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those three justices have said
at various
times that they feel the lower
courts aren't

11:54.847 --> 12:00.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
giving the right recognized by
the Second
Amendment the due that it should
have, and

12:00.987 --> 12:06.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they are all over the map
in how they
examine restrictions on guns.
And it's time,

12:06.326 --> 12:09.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they feel, for the court to step
back into
this area.

12:09.562 --> 12:13.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: OK, Evan, let's take
a step from
these two branches of government
and talk

12:13.733 --> 12:17.670 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more specifically about the
business branch
of government, as it were.

12:17.704 --> 12:23.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a business incentive
which has very
little to do with the laws about
why guns

12:23.209 --> 12:25.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
continue to be sold.

12:25.078 --> 12:26.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVAN OSNOS, "The New Yorker":
Well, this is
the thing I think that is sort
of a paradox,

12:26.846 --> 12:30.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is at this very moment when we
look at the
effects that guns has had on the
country in

12:30.683 --> 12:35.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the last two weeks, the gun
business is actually
doing better than ever.

12:35.555 --> 12:41.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Smith &amp; Wesson, the largest U.S.
gun manufacturer,
their stock price increased 10
percent by

12:41.361 --> 12:46.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the time the market opened the
day after Orlando.
What's going on? The answer is
that the industry

12:46.265 --> 12:50.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
occupies a very unique place in
American culture.
It's almost insulated from
business pressures

12:50.503 --> 12:55.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because of a law that was passed
in Congress
in 2005, meaning that if
somebody wanted to

12:55.575 --> 12:58.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bring a lawsuit, they couldn't
do it now.

12:58.044 --> 13:02.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's very hard to do it. One of
the things
we heard in the segment was
about this lawsuit

13:02.482 --> 13:06.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Connecticut, and that lawsuit
is enormously
important, because what it's
going to try

13:06.586 --> 13:12.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do is to figure out if the
gun industry
today, which has basically been
able to profit

13:12.392 --> 13:15.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the period in which mass
shootings have
elevated the fear, have elevated
people's

13:16.029 --> 13:21.668 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
desire to own a gun for
self-defense, whether
in fact the kinds of civil cases
that have

13:21.701 --> 13:26.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in the past have shaped
industry's behavior,
whether we're talking about BP,
for instance,

13:26.072 --> 13:29.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with oil, or whether we're
talking about tobacco
and how they market, whether in
fact they

13:29.976 --> 13:34.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will be shaped by their role in
these kinds
of national tragedies.

13:34.347 --> 13:39.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Lisa, just as we
have been talking,
a second effort at gun control
in the Senate

13:39.752 --> 13:42.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this afternoon has failed. Now,
here is my
question about that, though.

13:43.022 --> 13:48.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As Evan just said, there's a
distinct difference
between an argument about gun
control and

13:48.327 --> 13:53.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
self-defense. Self-defense seems
like something
everybody can get behind. Is
that the argument

13:53.399 --> 13:56.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that is playing out on the floor
of the Senate
or is it something more arcane?

13:56.035 --> 13:58.204 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: It's both.

13:58.237 --> 14:01.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The biggest argument to pay
attention to I
think for the endgame right now
is the argument

14:01.841 --> 14:05.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the no-fly or terror watch
list. And
I say this because, while
today's votes, we

14:05.912 --> 14:10.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do not expect to be meaningful,
there is a
compromise effort under way led
by Susan Collins

14:10.383 --> 14:12.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Maine just trying to pass
something.

14:12.552 --> 14:17.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have seen even Donald
Trump express
interest in somehow preventing
more people

14:17.056 --> 14:18.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the no-fly list from being
able to get
guns.

14:18.891 --> 14:20.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: That's something we
have heard
the president talk about too.

14:20.393 --> 14:22.095 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

14:22.128 --> 14:24.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the president, Democrats,
they all talk
sort of similar. But the
difference there

14:24.764 --> 14:30.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in is in the specifics. And it's
about Republicans'
mistrust of government having a
list of Americans

14:30.436 --> 14:32.238 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that it can block from having a
gun.

14:32.271 --> 14:35.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The list is not public, you
don't know when
you're on the list, and
Republicans say that's

14:36.008 --> 14:41.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a problem. Now, they err on the
side of let's
not -- let's err on the side of
allowing more

14:41.681 --> 14:46.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people the ability to buy guns.
Democrats
say no. Let's err on the side of
preventing

14:46.552 --> 14:49.856 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
people who we think are
dangerous from having
guns. That's what they're
working out right

14:49.889 --> 14:51.657 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

14:51.691 --> 14:56.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, at the Supreme
Court or in
the courts in general, is there
a long line

14:56.195 --> 15:02.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of gun debates headed for the
high court or
does it pretty much stop at
appeals courts?

15:02.402 --> 15:06.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does it pretty much stop farther
down the
line, so the court waits for
conflict?

15:06.806 --> 15:09.942 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE: The court will
wait for a conflict.

15:09.976 --> 15:15.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they may get one involving
Maryland's
ban on assault weapons. That
right now is

15:15.314 --> 15:20.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the Fourth Circuit Court of
Appeals and
was argued in May, so a decision
could come

15:20.853 --> 15:27.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
any day. But there's another
factor too, Gwen,
that I think comes into play
here. And that

15:27.393 --> 15:34.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is, the New York case that the
Supreme Court
didn't take today wasn't the
major challenge.

15:34.834 --> 15:39.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The federal appellate court that
ruled in
the Connecticut case also had
the New York

15:39.739 --> 15:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- another New York challenge at
the same
time and uphold New York's ban
back in October.

15:46.112 --> 15:51.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In March, the largest gun rights
group in
New York decided not to go to
the Supreme

15:51.450 --> 15:56.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Court on the advice of their
lawyers, for
two reasons. One, Justice Scalia
was no longer

15:56.489 --> 16:00.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the bench, the champion of
the Second Amendment
individual right.

16:00.526 --> 16:07.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, two, we now have an
eight-justice court
and the possibility of a 4-4
split would mean

16:07.400 --> 16:12.705 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the lower court's opinion
upholding both
bans would stand in place. And
they didn't

16:12.738 --> 16:14.240 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
want that precedent set.

16:14.273 --> 16:16.042 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Fascinating.

16:16.075 --> 16:20.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Evan, in your piece in "The New
Yorker," you
talk about concealed-carry laws,
which, among

16:20.112 --> 16:24.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other things, has driven up the
number of
guns that have been sold, as has
multiple

16:24.650 --> 16:29.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gun ownership. One person can
buy, can own
eight guns. And that's happening
more and

16:29.121 --> 16:29.589 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
more.

16:29.622 --> 16:31.390 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVAN OSNOS: Right.

16:31.424 --> 16:33.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the thing we don't often
talk about,
which is that the biggest change
that's gone

16:33.226 --> 16:37.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on in the culture of guns and
the business
of guns over the last generation
is that you

16:37.230 --> 16:41.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can now legally carry them in
all kinds of
places you simply couldn't
before.

16:41.667 --> 16:46.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Two decades ago, you simply
couldn't leave
your house in many states, 22
states. It was

16:46.706 --> 16:50.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
either illegal or restricted
regulated to
go outside with a gun. It's now
legal in all

16:50.743 --> 16:55.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
50 states. And this is really
the beginning,
I think, not the end, of a kind
of national

16:55.781 --> 17:00.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
political conversation about
whether or not
we are ready for that, whether
or not people

17:00.486 --> 17:02.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accept that and where they
accept that.

17:02.455 --> 17:06.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the reasons I think why
the court has
been reluctant to weigh in to
what everybody

17:06.259 --> 17:11.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agrees is probably the next
great frontier
in Second Amendment law, which
is where can

17:11.864 --> 17:16.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you carry and why, is because
you see these
radical differences in place to
place.

17:16.569 --> 17:19.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so far, what has happened is
that the
courts have basically said we're
going to

17:19.338 --> 17:23.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
leave it to these local
governments, state
governments and lower
governments to decide

17:23.476 --> 17:24.510 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
who can carry a gun and why.

17:24.543 --> 17:26.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Lisa, final thought?

17:26.345 --> 17:28.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And I think
here's why we
see the difference in politics
between the

17:28.147 --> 17:33.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American landscape. We see, as a
percentage,
fewer gun owners, but they are
owning more

17:33.085 --> 17:38.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
guns. Just like we see in so
many issues,
it's becoming concentrated in
very vocal minorities,

17:38.391 --> 17:40.559 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but they're controlling the
debate.

17:40.593 --> 17:45.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lisa Desjardins, Evan Osnos at
"The New Yorker"
and Marcia Coyle of "The
National Law Journal,"

17:45.665 --> 17:49.135 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
thank you all very much.

17:49.168 --> 17:52.538 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARCIA COYLE: Pleasure.

17:52.571 --> 17:57.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EVAN OSNOS: Thanks, Gwen.

17:57.143 --> 18:01.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now we turn to
Iraq.

18:01.047 --> 18:07.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The offensive to retake the city
of Fallujah,
held by ISIS for more than two
years, is proceeding

18:07.987 --> 18:13.859 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
much more quickly than
anticipated. But tens
of thousands of its residents
have been forced

18:13.893 --> 18:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the fighting into the desert,
as temperatures
soar, without services, or even
water in many

18:20.299 --> 18:22.101 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cases.

18:22.134 --> 18:26.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We turn to special correspondent
Jane Arraf.
She's in Baghdad now, where she
is on assignment

18:26.339 --> 18:28.441 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for The Christian Science
Monitor.

18:28.474 --> 18:34.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jane, you were just in Fallujah
yesterday.
And is it the case this
operation has been

18:34.480 --> 18:36.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going much faster than expected?

18:36.248 --> 18:39.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE ARRAF: Well, Judy, it has
been going
faster certainly than some of
the previous

18:39.819 --> 18:43.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
operations, including the battle
for the provincial
capital Anbar.

18:43.422 --> 18:49.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think we have to remember
that Fallujah
is a different case. Fallujah
had up to 100,000

18:49.061 --> 18:54.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people in it. And it was where
ISIS first
came into, where they tried to
persuade Iraqis

18:54.900 --> 18:57.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
that they were a better
alternative than the
Iraqi government.

18:57.870 --> 19:03.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They didn't lay the land mines,
they didn't
lay the improvised explosives
the same way

19:03.242 --> 19:08.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they riddled other cities
with. It was
actually faster for the special
forces that

19:08.347 --> 19:12.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we were with to actually go
through there
and fight.

19:12.418 --> 19:19.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Having said that, they have not
in fact liberated
Fallujah, in the sense that the
Iraqi government

19:19.191 --> 19:24.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
likes to say that they have.
Now, Iraqi special
forces, including the commander,
who we spoke

19:24.697 --> 19:30.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with, says that they have now
cleared 75 percent
of the city.

19:30.202 --> 19:35.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
American military sources say
they think that's
closer to 25 percent. And they
say that the

19:35.608 --> 19:41.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
effort is continuing. But as
it's continuing,
as you pointed out, there is
absolute tragedy

19:41.814 --> 19:45.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the outskirts of Fallujah
with all these
civilians trying to flea.

19:45.818 --> 19:52.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, tell us
about that. Who
stayed in Fallujah when ISIS had
control,

19:52.525 --> 19:54.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and what's happening to those
people?

19:54.360 --> 19:59.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE ARRAF: A lot of people did
leave at the
beginning, but then a lot of
people stayed

19:59.598 --> 20:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for a variety of reasons.

20:01.634 --> 20:06.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when it got to two years in,
essentially,
they weren't allowed to leave.
So, the people

20:06.939 --> 20:10.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that I was speaking with, mostly
women and
children, because they were
separated from

20:10.276 --> 20:16.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
their husbands and their
brothers as the Iraqi
security forces tried to weed
out suspected

20:16.048 --> 20:21.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS fighters from civilians
fleeing, were
telling us, were telling me that
they had

20:21.687 --> 20:25.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
been without real food for weeks
on end.

20:25.891 --> 20:32.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, as the siege of Fallujah
intensified,
ISIS itself started running out
of food, and

20:32.198 --> 20:37.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it started giving food only to
those tribes,
those families that were loyal
to it. So,

20:37.736 --> 20:41.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
groups of women who I spoke with
said that
they had been living on the only
thing they

20:41.373 --> 20:46.245 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
could afford, which was
basically dried dates
that were meant for animal feed.

20:46.278 --> 20:50.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They weren't allowed to leave
the city. If
they could leave the city, it
was through

20:50.249 --> 20:55.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
bribery. And at this point,
people just don't
have the money. So, they
basically stayed,

20:55.221 --> 21:01.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Judy, because they had to stay.
It is when
ISIS was driven back and the
floodgates opened

21:01.894 --> 21:09.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and up to 80,000 people fled
over the past
three days, just last week, that
things got

21:09.235 --> 21:10.970 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
really dire.

21:11.003 --> 21:15.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some people were actually killed
trying to
leave. I met a man with the
remainder of his

21:15.774 --> 21:22.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
family in an ambulance in
Fallujah being evacuated
by Iraqi security forces who has
lost three

21:22.047 --> 21:27.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of his daughters and his wife.
As they were
leaving, they were hit by either
a mortar

21:27.119 --> 21:28.921 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or a rocket.

21:28.954 --> 21:32.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He ended up burying two of his
daughters in
the grounds in the hospital. And
then he couldn't

21:32.925 --> 21:37.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leave until Iraqi security
forces rescued
him. There are other people who
drowned trying

21:37.329 --> 21:39.064 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to leave.

21:39.098 --> 21:43.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But even those who survive,
Judy, are living
in dire circumstances. There is
no water.

21:43.435 --> 21:48.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no consistent water
supply. There
is not even shelter. I have met
pregnant women

21:48.174 --> 21:51.343 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
